{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e4f8dffd-7acc-4741-a9f4-a5863cff6d6d","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest 3.2+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous initialization here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs after constructor)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup work here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (runs after each test)\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` replaces the old property-setter pattern (available since MSTest 3.2+)\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement for async setup that runs after the constructor\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** — implement for async teardown\n- You can still use `[TestInitialize]` / `[TestCleanup]` attributes if you prefer method-based lifecycle hooks, but the interfaces give you a cleaner DI-friendly pattern","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"962b5b36-c163-4b9d-b358-1ed7eabf523d","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"BD04:7B45F:1DBC54C:21A81E8:6A07CBB9"},"id":"74ebab81-a0a5-402d-b983-2c130a43efef","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:43:29.330Z","parentId":"319c3d4c-973f-490c-a279-52ff61350a7f"}
